WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Okay, Joe, we are ready.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Today is Wednesday, May 26, 2011.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:33.000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Low History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I am in Austin, Texas with our videographer for the project, Mr. John Bishop.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And we are here to interview Mr. James Oscar Jones for the joint project being conducted by the Library of Congress in the Smithsonian,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:59.000
and then more particularly Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture, excuse me, the new Civil Rights History project,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
the National Civil Rights History series.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:05.000
This Jones is going to be with you if you think this person down.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Thank you.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:07.000
Thank you.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
As I mentioned before, we turned on the camera today.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.000
I thought we'd start with just to sketch your family history, because I know it will have a lot to do with the course of your life.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And so I'm up here about where you're born, where you came up, parents?

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Glad to appear as Ernest Jones and mom, Curtis Jones, that my father born and raised on the farm, that was his life.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
That's what he loved to do.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:47.000
I'm a member of a family of 10 children, six boys and four girls.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And the first five children was born as Routin, because that dad was Routin, and he was killed cutting logs in the wood.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:10.000
And so that first five were very young when he died, and then my dad Ernest Jones married my mama, and his five more children.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:18.000
But my dad raised all 10 of us, because it was very, very young when that dad got killed.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And basically what he did was, they were very disciplined, had a seven-grade education, mom had a seven-grade education, but very bright, very brilliant people.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And one of the ambition they had, and they gave us, as we were a little kids, he had two gold for us.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
He wanted all of us to be educated, and he wanted to see all 10 of us in heaven.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And so he wanted us to be committed to church, hard work, and school.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:09.000
So I had the pleasure of going to school all the way through elementary, all the way through high school, and I never missed a day.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
He was mean and tough on us going to school.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:26.000
We had to get up four o'clock in the morning, milk the cows, feed the pigs, and do all of this, walk one mile from the house to the dirt road where the bus came by.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And kissed the bus at 6.45, and you had to do that now, you were sure that was your, and it applied to everybody, the girls and boys the same way.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:48.000
So we had the fortune of understanding work very early, and going to school very early, and that's kind of what dad shaped.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:56.000
He said he was when he bought his first acre of land. He was 13 years old.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:02.000
He paid $1.25, and it took him six months to make that $1.25.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:17.000
So the farm we grew up on were part of Frank McKinney, which is a German McKinney, which is my mama's side, but then he added to the acreage, and grew us a good, good farm.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Or we farm cotton corn, and then we had, because he couldn't borrow any money from the farmers home administration those days.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:35.000
He created a large piece of the farm, and we had peach orchards, bearers, and all of that.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And the cash money we made from the seller of the fruit and vegetables is what money he used to farm the cotton corn.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:50.000
How was the nature of Willisville in those days?

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Well, when I was a little boy, there was a lot of folks there.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:02.000
It never has been an incorporated town, it's just a village.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:14.000
I would say when I grew up two or three hundred kids, maybe, and what happened is most of the kids grew up with me.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:23.000
My graded and took off, wanted to draw Dallas, Texas, Houston, Texas, all those places looking for work.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:32.000
We were the only farm, black farm group in Willisville with a farm.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
All the other kids worked on farms, but they were not there.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:43.000
It was primarily white farmers, and that was a heart, because they weren't allowed to go to school.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:52.000
They came to school, maybe I have a Thanksgiving, but by March it was time to start telling us all again, they had to come back to work.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So a lot of them didn't have an opportunity to go to school from grade one to high school.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:08.000
How did your father manage the farm without all that extra help that would have been there in the sense every day of school?

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Well, what he did was all of us was big enough to do some of the older sisters and brothers.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:25.000
But also, he always used, and there were some older kids who dropped out of school and just kind of wondered.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:30.000
And he would go get those kids and bring them back, and they would work there with us.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And he would pay them at the end of the day, at the end of the week.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.000
They were excited about that, because when they worked on other farms, they didn't own a lot of time.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
They would put on the books.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And the problem with that system was they never made enough money, they never worked hard enough to pay off those debts.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
You were always, and then dad would have them to come over and set them on to stay fair, was taking place.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:04.000
And he would say, come on over here, late in the evening, I'll give you a little work so you have a few bucks to go to the fair.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
You know, and everybody wanted to go to the fair, but they didn't have it in the minus, so that's how dad helped out.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And then there was gracious to come over and work at our place as well.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:22.000
We've heard some, tell them about church, and were they active in the end of the week, see?

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
My mama was very active.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Dad stayed very close to the farm, day in, day out.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:37.000
But Sunday was a day you couldn't test the farm.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And that was a day you had no choice but to get up and down the dirt road and find the desk going to church.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:51.000
All day long church, that one share was like the city folk, I ate a clock, I ate a 12 o'clock, no.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:00.000
You went to church in the morning, and when you got out of that church, you went to another church because my mom had a beautiful singing voice.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:09.000
And everybody in the neighborhood wanted to come sing, we hop in the back of the truck and go to that place, and then somebody had a five o'clock mean, we go to that church.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
So it was church, church, church, church.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
Oh yeah, I had plenty of church.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:21.000
Tell them to turn that there, you know, there's sense of politics and race relations.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:32.000
My mama, everybody called my mother Vic, matter of fact when she passed away, and they had the name Perdis Jones.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And a lot of folks call her funeral home in Magnolia, said, who is this Perdis Jones?

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:45.000
So they undertake her, say, well, everybody know her as Vic.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And what he said that people from all over the country had left, what did they walk in?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
So y'all cannot have that funeral.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:59.000
Postpone that funeral because we want to come home to that funeral, and that's what the word got out of it was Vic.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:03.000
So hundreds and hundreds of people came in.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:13.000
But mama on, she was very active in organizations in WCP, in Magnolia, that was the closest place.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
She would go to those meetings.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.000
And when she would come back, she would talk to the kids at church.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
Now, we got to do something.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:31.000
They talked about that meeting, how we can do better, how we, how folks need to learn, how to fix up their own homes, and all that,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
and stop depending on outside people.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And then she would, when they would have those meetings, she and her sister would throw people back and they would pick up truck and they would go on.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
And it was not a thing where she would go ask parents permission.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:54.000
She would just get that old truck and just go through and get in the truck, get in this truck and they would go to the meetings.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So the kids, you know, growing up in a rural area, they would go out and jumping back at the truck and go somewhere.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:01.000
It was not a lot.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And she was, and that was her.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
She was just very active all over the place.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And when she learned about what people were doing, she would come back to church and talk to church people about what we need to do is we need to get the men together to do this and women get together because that's the kind of thing she would learn from the end of the SAP meeting.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:43.000
Do you remember, say, let us think a few things for the 50s and, you know, from Brownby Board to Montgomery to Little Rock, especially Little Rock in where you were.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And this thing has talked a lot about how church people through your life, this one.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:58.000
The one thing I remember was in the Brown case.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:05.000
Thurgood Marshall and my dad always had this big old radio, huge radio.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And it was very powerful.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
And as a matter of fact, in Williamsville, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, Arkansas, we could pick up St. Louis.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
And that's how it would kept up with baseball.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
All we had to radio on.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:22.000
And Mr. Third gear made a statement that was on the radio.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:31.000
He wanted every Negro in America to stand still that one day at noon because the...

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Mr. Jones, we just had a brief pause to check the camera.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:50.000
You would just start talking about Brown and you were saying important things about your dad and Williamsville, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:56.000
They were so amazed by that.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:02.000
And Mr. Third gear put out a radio.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:16.000
And on that day, 12 noon is the only grocery store that stands still at 12 noon because of the Supreme Court is fixing to make an announcement.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:23.000
And that announcement and that Supreme Court has got to change this whole nation.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So, daddy, you know, said, and he went to the little school, sweet home where I was going to school.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:42.000
He went down there and told the teachers about it and said that we need to make sure everybody here what is about to be said.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So, he had that much politics in his hair.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And people got all the radios and really was listening for that announcement.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:01.000
So, he stayed on the top of stuff the same way he was that same way about farming.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:07.000
He could not borrow money from the Farmers Home Administration.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:15.000
But what he would do is that he kept his eyes very close on what white farmers were doing.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:29.000
And some of the wealthier white farmers would use the spiles and they would break a plow and they had the ability to go and get in mind and get to know it.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:35.000
And what he did was he would ask those black guys working for those white owners.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Is what they're going to do with that plow?

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
Oh, nothing. We've already gone and got it.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:49.000
I want to see if I can get that plow. So, he would go and say, Mr. Walmart, I just want that plow. He can have his bro.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And he would take it up to the little school we went to at vocational school.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:01.000
And the kids would experiment with welding that back. And so, we would use those plows.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And those were accumulation that he had to pay for as part of his farmers.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
He was on top of the farmer as well as the political side of the thing.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And the fact that your father owns his own farm, how much of that matter in two ways? One in relation to other members of the black community locally.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:44.000
And in relation to maybe how your life unfolded in a sense of how you measured your own possibilities and independence.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:57.000
The first part on the farm side, what mom and dad had, people who lived on other farms and they had very poor houses.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:05.000
He knew that if we did any kind of work on those houses, they would get tossed off the farm.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And what he would do, he would have us to go and help them to crack a house and all that kind of stuff.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:25.000
We would go cut wood and put it on the inside to seal the holes and everything. And that was no cost.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:29.000
And that was something we, his son, we had to do it.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And when, and if we, I remember the one time my brother under me, he took a quarter of a missile later, he says, you don't do so much.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And we're just so thankful. Here, you all take this quarter, I told you, I don't take no money. You know, dad, I don't want to, this is something he wants us to do for folks.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And we went home and dad would say, did your boy take in the money? I said no sir. I said, just a little bit.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:01.000
He said, well, how much money did I remember? I don't remember how many. He said, game a quarter, give me that quarter.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And so he took the quarter and we went to church, Sunday. He made just to take that quarter up to the poor pit and put it in an offering.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:21.000
He could not spit it. And we did that for a lot of elderly people. And so he would just, that kind of carried.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:39.000
On the, on the other side, I was being kind of trained to do something pretty good, but I didn't see it because dad and mom will go to the school

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:58.000
and have all these talks with the teachers. And what they were talking about, late on, I learned from my older sisters and brothers is that they said, James, dad and mom is there, probably, a year or a smart.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And they are telling those teachers to push you, push you real hard because you got to smile.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And, but I learned that later because I noticed I always have to do everything at school, everything.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:21.000
We have a little school program. Now we want you to be the MC. We want you to start that group. We want you to be over the agriculture program.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:30.000
And I had all the assignment. And so when I would come home, I didn't get a chance to go out and play because I had to do all these things.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:38.000
And they were coming. Now, now, now, James, you got to get all that stuff done. So between feeding the hogs and the chicken and all that. And doing that, but that time is dark.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:47.000
And I also played basketball and the basketball team. But I didn't see anything in that.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:55.000
But when I got a little further in school toward the 11th grade, I could see it.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:03.000
We want you to do some marvelous things, James. And you got your skills, you smart, you do good work in school.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:14.000
You go in place. That's when they started encouraging me. And then when that happened, I was playing basketball.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:25.000
And this was a real shock to me. Because we worked hard, but dad didn't give you no money. And we would always ask dad, why do you, other kids come work on a farm?

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:37.000
Why do you pay them, but you don't pay us? He said, that's because I'm saving for hard time. So this was the clearest thing. Well dad is pretty hard.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:47.000
He said, no, you'll even know what hard time is. You got a place to stay. You got clothes, you're teaching us that you don't know what a hard time is.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:56.000
And then the guys way across what we call it, Creek, the bus didn't go with us. They were basketball guys.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:06.000
They would come over to our house and stay with us. And the bus would come down his dirt road. And we were playing in this district tournament.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:17.000
And dad came up to us and he had like $25 and change and what did I build?

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:32.000
He said, James, take this and your boys got a little money to spend. And he said, and the girls by them ice cream, like nickel and buy the girls and ice cream and all that.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:41.000
So what we got to the jail is ice cream. And so the word was round, he's rich.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:57.000
He's rich. He's rich. So a lot of the kids don't call him he rich. If I am, I don't know anybody. I don't see the old.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
You saw the same money I saw at that one ball game.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:32.000
And they went to school as they left. But that was after they left. And in my case, I stayed there.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:42.000
And my oldest sister and brother went right letters and say, how you doing in school and semi-agreed. And I was sitting in my grade and we were semi-odd dollar.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And back in those days, a dollar man, he was filthy rich.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:58.000
I'm interested. We'll talk about everything that's going to happen at in Pine Bluff after you get down 61 and especially in 63.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:06.000
But I'm curious if how much the early 60s were late 50s or early 60s making an impact on you.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:14.000
Little rock and 57, sitting in Greensboro in 60, all of what happened quickly after that.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:35.000
The one big favor, not favor, but the one thing that prepared me really well for that is that because Daddy and Mama listened to the radio and they paid attention to that kind of stuff.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:56.000
And they were really on top of Central High. And I remember one time Mama said to me, she said, son, if you ever put it in that situation, don't turn it down.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:13.000
You go follow with it. And that was a result of what I didn't realize was that Mama and my aunt and Daddy in the early days they had buses come through a small town.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And even in those days they were the only black folks that were getting that bus on the front seat and taking us with us.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And then that kind of came back to me. I said, oh, we integrated the bus line because when Central High came through it kind of, and over her words, that whenever you get an opportunity to do something for other people, don't be afraid.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Because you didn't come from an afraid. She said, it was dangerous when y'all went to weigh your own kind.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Too many people didn't like that. And y'all been through it and you're seeing it. And you can, when the opportunity comes, don't go to the back of the line.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:17.000
You go to the head of the line and be brave about it. Now they did talk about that. And when I went to, went off the school, you know, I had all that in my hair.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:32.000
I wasn't looking for anything. But when I saw, when I got to Pine Bluff in the city, you saw real, real segregation because it was a city in Williamsville, Arkansas, Arkansas.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:38.000
You're down to war in the woods and when you go to town you would see it. But when I got there, I really saw it.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:48.000
But I wasn't organized, but I saw it as I went downtown and I saw all the holidays and all those.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:24:00.000
I looked at it and I saw, the whole thing I saw black folks were made. So that registered in my mind. When I went back home, I shared with them.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:28.000
He said, well, son, if you, I'm not going to tell you what to do with this word, my mom will say it to me. If you go somewhere and y'all like, because we would travel sometime in the sport, don't you never go through a back door.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:35.000
If wise go through the back door, you go through the front door. Now, I heard that from her.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:36.000
Yeah.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.000
What was your moment ago?

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:45.000
That your family, you know, you were gone and waged your own cotton. Can you tell that story just a little bit about that?

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:57.000
Well, kids who lived on a plantation, they would work hard and you have these 10 and 12 foot long.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:09.000
And when you picked them which cotton, you were hidden six to five and some guy was really good and hit as much as eight.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:17.000
But when they brought their bags to the chin, white people didn't let them stay that way, they were on cotton.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:30.000
So they would bring the bags and drop them. They'd go back. Now, in my case, daddy and mama, aunt, nuh, and uncle Bluford went to the gin.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:37.000
Now, my mama, dad and uncle and aunt T, were gunpacking black folks.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:45.000
They would sit right at the gin with them double-barred shotgun and two-shell between their fingers.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:56.000
And when we got our cotton, come on boys. And they would go up that way, we were our own cotton.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:03.000
Now, the kids who would bring that cotton to the gin, they couldn't weigh that.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And we would sit there and watch this. Sometimes those bags would be seven to pounds of cotton.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:14.000
And these guys would ask each other, well, John, what do you think?

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
Oh, I'll miss you.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:22.000
Oh, give it take four to one pound. Oh, pretty good old boy. Give them benefit of four to seven pounds.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:26.000
So that's four to pound. They were taken away from them.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:34.000
So I was at that and witnessed that. Now, the fun kind of thing was, being clearly and just and all of us,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:40.000
we felt pretty comfortable because mama, not nuh, was at with those guns.

