00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
And then that's what he said.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:44.000
But we need a black person and you've already done all this stuff.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:58.000
And he said, if you went into one of the white restaurants and was arrested, what would your parents say?

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:09.000
They would come up here and they would come to the jail house and they would say, James, is this what you want to do?

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:16.000
And if I say yes, he said, we're doing whatever you need, I should support you and they would go back home.

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:18.000
He said, really?

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:21.000
They wouldn't ask him that.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:41.000
I said because they talked to me, law the fond of doing things about this kind of stuff, if you get involved and stuff and they talk about, don't you ever go through white doors, back doors, you go through the front of the front door and white people go, you go through it too.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:44.000
He said, whoa, man, you're mama's civil right?

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:48.000
Well, I guess not because I don't know what to do.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:55.000
The whole lot to do, but I did tell them, I shared with them how mom and him wrote the bus and he said, yeah, that's civil rights stuff.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:40:00.000
I said, I didn't know what, but that just, to me, that's how they were.

