01:56:02.000 --> 01:56:06.000
One telling important story about the tensions inside

01:56:06.000 --> 01:56:08.000
say that you'll work at sharecroppers,

01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:12.000
and people have different ideas about how to go at these problems.

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:15.000
With the sharecroppers,

01:56:15.000 --> 01:56:23.000
they're folks who feel they deserve being paid a lot of money.

01:56:23.000 --> 01:56:29.000
No identification, what fault, but just to do it.

01:56:29.000 --> 01:56:33.000
What my assignment was at sharecroppers

01:56:33.000 --> 01:56:40.000
was to go identify in Virginia, Georgia,

01:56:40.000 --> 01:56:47.000
Florida, South Carolina, small farmers.

01:56:47.000 --> 01:56:55.000
And I did not deal with the inside of that mechanism.

01:56:56.000 --> 01:57:00.000
I told them, I think there are some opportunities for them to

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:05.000
sell that product and make some of my festinene I worked on.

01:57:05.000 --> 01:57:12.000
And I worked with national change stores and the big change stores.

01:57:12.000 --> 01:57:16.000
And I learned in that circle,

01:57:16.000 --> 01:57:23.000
most of the stores was looking for black farmers, small farmers product.

01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:29.000
Closer, fresher, a lot cheaper because of the distance.

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:31.000
And that worked fine.

01:57:31.000 --> 01:57:34.000
That was kind of easy.

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:44.000
But what had some on black is they were talking about the money,

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:48.000
the big farmers making, which was not always true.

01:57:48.000 --> 01:57:51.000
And shipping it all into the country,

01:57:51.000 --> 01:57:54.000
you need a lot of volume.

01:57:54.000 --> 01:58:01.000
And they weren't looking over the fact that I got five acres of tomatoes

01:58:01.000 --> 01:58:03.000
that I can harvest four times.

01:58:03.000 --> 01:58:07.000
And I can send it right here to Crocus and Crocus by,

01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:10.000
